.\" Symlink Manual Page
.\" Generated: 2026-03-08
.\"
.TH SYMLINK 1 "March 2026" "symlink 1.4.0" "User Commands"
.\"
.SH NAME
symlink \- create symlinks in /usr/local/bin for executables
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B symlink
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.IR scriptpath ...
.br
.B symlink
.B \-S
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.RI [ startpath ]
.br
.B symlink
.B \-l
.RI [ startpath ]
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B symlink
creates symbolic links in
.I /usr/local/bin
(or a custom target directory) for executable scripts, making them
accessible system-wide. It supports both direct file linking and batch
processing via
.I .symlink
configuration files.
.PP
The utility automatically elevates to root privileges via
.BR sudo (8)
when not already running as root. In interactive mode (stdin is a
terminal), confirmation prompts are enabled by default.
.PP
Three modes of operation are available:
.TP
.B Direct Linking
Specify one or more script paths as arguments. Each script is linked
into the target directory using its basename.
.TP
.B Scan Mode (\-S)
Recursively search a directory tree (max depth 5) for
.I .symlink
batch files and process all entries found.
.TP
.B List Mode (\-l)
Display the contents of
.I .symlink
files found in the directory tree without creating any links.
.\"
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-S ", " \-\-scan\-symlink
Scan for
.I .symlink
files and process them. Searches up to 5 directory levels deep.
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-list
List
.I .symlink
file contents only (no linking). Cannot be combined with
.BR \-S .
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-target\-dir " " \fIDIR\fR
Set the target directory for symlink creation. Default is
.IR /usr/local/bin .
Can also be set via the
.B DEFAULT_TARGET_DIR
environment variable.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-delete\-broken\-symlinks
Remove broken symlinks in the target directory after processing.
.TP
.BR \-P ", " \-\-no\-prompt
Skip all confirmation prompts. Useful for scripted or non-interactive
operation.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-dry\-run
Preview changes without making them. Shows what would be created,
replaced, or skipped.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Enable detailed output showing each operation as it is performed.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress verbose output (opposite of
.BR \-v ).
.TP
.BR \-D ", " \-\-debug
Enable debug mode with detailed trace logging to
.IR /tmp/symlink\-trace\-<user>\-<pid>.log .
Can also be enabled via the
.B SYMLINK_DEBUG
environment variable.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display help message and exit.
.PP
Short options may be combined:
.B \-SPd
is equivalent to
.BR "\-S \-P \-d" .
.\"
.SH .SYMLINK FILE FORMAT
A
.I .symlink
file defines which executables in a directory should be linked into
the target directory. Each line specifies a source file and optional
link names.
.PP
.RS
.I source
.RI [ linkname ...]
.RE
.PP
Paths are relative to the
.I .symlink
file location.
.SS Parsing Rules
.TP
.B 1.
Strip inline comments
.RB ( #
to end of line).
.TP
.B 2.
Trim leading and trailing whitespace.
.TP
.B 3.
Skip empty lines.
.TP
.B 4.
First token is the source file (supports
.B \e\
for literal spaces in filenames). Remaining tokens are link names.
.TP
.B 5.
If no link names are specified, the basename of the source is used.
.TP
.B 6.
Link names do NOT support spaces (commands in /usr/local/bin should not
have spaces).
.SS Examples
.PP
.nf
.RS
# Comments start with #
  # Indented comments are valid

script1                    # \(-> script1
tools/script2              # \(-> script2
build.bash build           # \(-> build (custom name)
util.sh helper util\-cmd    # \(-> helper AND util\-cmd
my\e script.sh              # \(-> my script.sh (escaped space)
my\e script.sh myscript     # \(-> myscript
.RE
.fi
.\"
.SH SAFETY
.B symlink
includes multiple safety mechanisms to prevent accidental damage to
the system:
.TP
.B Critical File Protection
53 critical system binaries (including
.BR bash ", " sudo ", " ls ", " rm ", " cp ", " mv ", " grep ", " sed )
are protected from accidental replacement. In non-interactive mode,
attempts to overwrite these files are silently skipped unless
.B SYMLINK_FORCE_CRITICAL
is set. In interactive mode, an explicit confirmation is required.
.TP
.B Scan Depth Limiting
Directory scanning is limited to 5 levels deep
.RB ( FIND_MAX_DEPTH )
to prevent excessive traversal.
.TP
.B Path Resolution Timeout
A 2-second timeout is applied when resolving source file paths via
.BR realpath (1),
preventing hangs on unresponsive filesystems.
.TP
.B Target Directory Restrictions
Scanning within the target directory itself
.RI ( /usr/local/bin
by default) is restricted to prevent recursive symlink creation.
.TP
.B Auto\-Sudo Elevation
The script automatically re-executes itself under
.BR sudo (8)
when not running as root, ensuring proper privileges without
requiring the user to remember to prefix with sudo.
.\"
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
General error.
.TP
.B 2
Permission denied.
.TP
.B 3
File not found.
.TP
.B 22
Invalid option (EINVAL).
.TP
.B 50
No .symlink files found during scan.
.\"
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SYMLINK_DEBUG
Set to
.B 1
to enable debug mode. Equivalent to the
.B \-D
option. Writes trace output to
.IR /tmp/symlink\-trace\-<user>\-<pid>.log .
.TP
.B SYMLINK_FORCE_CRITICAL
Set to
.B 1
to allow replacement of critical system files in non-interactive
mode. Use with extreme caution.
.TP
.B DEFAULT_TARGET_DIR
Override the default target directory for symlink creation.
Defaults to
.IR /usr/local/bin .
.\"
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/local/bin
Default target directory for created symlinks.
.TP
.I .symlink
Configuration files defining executables to link. Searched recursively
during scan mode
.RB ( \-S ).
.TP
.I /tmp/symlink\-trace\-<user>\-<pid>.log
Debug trace log created when debug mode is enabled.
.TP
.I /usr/local/share/man/man1/symlink.1
This manual page.
.\"
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Batch Processing (Primary Use Case)
.TP
.B sudo symlink \-SPd /my/scripts
Scan for .symlink files, skip prompts, and clean broken links.
.TP
.B sudo symlink \-SPd
Scan the current directory.
.TP
.B symlink \-l /path/to/projects
List .symlink file contents without creating links.
.\"
.SS Direct Linking
.TP
.B sudo symlink /path/to/script
Create a symlink for a single script.
.TP
.B symlink \-n ./my\-script.sh
Dry-run to preview changes.
.\"
.SS Debug and Diagnostics
.TP
.B symlink \-\-debug \-nSPd /path/to/scripts
Debug mode with dry-run scan.
.TP
.B SYMLINK_DEBUG=1 symlink \-SPd
Enable debug mode via environment variable.
.\"
.SS Custom Target Directory
.TP
.B sudo symlink \-t /opt/bin ./my\-script.sh
Create symlink in /opt/bin instead of /usr/local/bin.
.\"
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ln (1),
.BR sudo (8),
.BR find (1),
.BR realpath (1)
.\"
